english:
  title: Record of the Pure Wind Pavilion
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: "In the fourth month of summer in the year Gicho of Zhizheng, returning home to pay respects to my parents, I lodged at Naksaeng Station. The prefect of Gwangju, White Lord and his father, sent word and invited me, saying: \"North of the official residence, we have discovered the ancient foundation of the Pure Wind Pavilion. We have built a four-pillared structure there—truly the finest sight in our prefecture. Would you honor us with a record of it?\" I was pressed for time on my journey, so I replied: \"When I next go to the capital, I shall pass through and view it with my own eyes. Recording it need not wait long.\" \n\nThe following year, upon reaching Gwangju, White Lord had already been recalled, and another official, Master Lee, had taken his post for half a year. The heat was oppressive that season—even breathing felt like drawing in a single thread. At last I ascended to what they call the Pure Wind Pavilion. Leaning on my staff and loosening my robes, my spirit grew clear and fresh, my hair stirred by the breeze as if a cicada had shed its shell and emerged beyond the dust of this turbid world.\n\nMaster Lee set out wine and spoke at leisure: \"The four-pillar design is simple, true enough. But morning and evening sunlight falls from east and west, troubling our seated guests. So I have added eaves on both sides, extending southward five chi on each, and likewise to the north. Thus the pavilion grows somewhat wider and deeper. The plaster work is complete, and we were about to apply the colored finish when you arrived. Why not raise a cup to celebrate its completion and inscribe it with the date?\"\n\nSince I had already promised White Lord, I asked: how many years had the pavilion lain in ruin? Yet none of the elders could say. If so, then restoring what was lost is much the same as building anew. The Spring and Autumn Annals records that \"one should not write of building,\" yet elsewhere it asks, \"Why should not the Long Treasury of Lu be rebuilt?\" The sage's teaching runs deep indeed.\n\nObserving Gwangju, I see three sides ringed by high mountains, while the north, though distant, descends into low ground—the public offices and private dwellings nestle as if at the bottom of a well. When guests arrive, they lament this lowness and narrowness. Yet within mere paces lies this place of such rare clarity and elevation. The building of this pavilion need not fall under the judgment of those who forbid construction.\n\nAs for the meaning of \"pure wind,\" White Lord has already spoken of it fully, and I shall not labor the point further. White Lord is a fellow graduate of my year, and Master Lee a friend of kindred spirit. Both have earned renown for their integrity and diligence in office.\n\nRecorded in the sixth month of the year Gyeongin."
  footnotes:
    - The Spring and Autumn Annals contains discussions about when it is and is not appropriate to undertake construction projects. Lee Gok invokes this classical authority to justify the building of the pavilion.
    - The "Pure Wind" (청풍) is both the literal name of the pavilion and a metaphor for the refreshing clarity and virtue embodied in the place and the officials who built it.
